Got it — the PDF you uploaded is the Inception project (from 42 school).
It’s basically a system administration exercise using Docker where you must set up a small infrastructure.

Here’s a clear breakdown of what you need to do:

🔹 1. Environment setup

  • Work inside a Virtual Machine (VM).

  • Create a srcs/ folder where all configs will live.

  • At the project root, have a Makefile that:

    • Builds all Docker images.

    • Calls your docker-compose.yml.

🔹 2. Mandatory infrastructure

You need to create 3 services, each with its own Dockerfile:

  1. NGINX container

    • Acts as the entry point.

    • Must only allow TLSv1.2 or TLSv1.3.

    • Listens on port 443 only.

  2. WordPress container

    • Runs with php-fpm only (no nginx inside it).

    • Stores site files in a volume.

  3. MariaDB container

    • Dedicated to the database.

    • Stores DB in a volume.

    • Must have 2 users: one admin (but not named admin/administrator), and one normal user.

🔹 3. Networking & storage

  • Define a docker network in docker-compose.yml that connects all services.

  • Use volumes mapped to /home/<login>/data:

    • One for WordPress site files.

    • One for WordPress database.

  • Containers must restart automatically if they crash.

  • Forbidden hacks:

    • tail -f, sleep infinity, infinite loops, etc.

    • Don’t use --link, network: host, or latest tags.

🔹 4. Configuration

  • Use a .env file for environment variables (usernames, domain name, etc.).

  • Use Docker secrets or separate files for passwords.

  • Your domain name must resolve to your local IP:

    • Format: <login>.42.fr (e.g., wil.42.fr).

🔹 5. Bonus part (only if mandatory is perfect)

You can add extra services like:

  • Redis (caching for WordPress).

  • FTP server for WordPress volume.

  • Static website (not PHP).

  • Adminer (DB management).

  • Any other useful service (must justify during defense).

✅ In short:
You’ll write custom Dockerfiles for NGINX, WordPress, MariaDB, connect them with Docker Compose, secure with TLS, use volumes and networks, manage environment variables securely, and make sure the whole thing runs only through port 443 with your domain name.

🪜 Step-by-Step Walkthrough

1. Project structure

You need this tree:

bash
inception/
├── Makefile
├── srcs/
│   ├── docker-compose.yml
│   ├── .env
│   └── requirements/
│       ├── mariadb/
│       │   ├── Dockerfile
│       │   └── conf/
│       ├── wordpress/
│       │   ├── Dockerfile
│       │   └── conf/
│       └── nginx/
│           ├── Dockerfile
│           └── conf/
└── secrets/
    ├── db_root_password.txt
    ├── db_password.txt
    └── credentials.txt

2. Volumes

You must mount volumes under /home/<login>/data on the host:

  • /home/<login>/data/mariadb

  • /home/<login>/data/wordpress

3. Environment variables (srcs/.env)

Example:

ini
# Domain
DOMAIN_NAME=yourlogin.42.fr

# Database
MYSQL_DATABASE=wordpress
MYSQL_USER=wp_user
MYSQL_PASSWORD_FILE=/run/secrets/db_password
MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD_FILE=/run/secrets/db_root_password

# Wordpress
WORDPRESS_DB_HOST=mariadb:3306
WORDPRESS_DB_NAME=wordpress
WORDPRESS_DB_USER=wp_user
WORDPRESS_DB_PASSWORD_FILE=/run/secrets/db_password

4. Secrets (/secrets)

Files:

  • db_root_password.txt → root DB password

  • db_password.txt → WordPress user password

  • credentials.txt → (optional) store admin credentials

These must not be in git.

5. MariaDB container (srcs/requirements/mariadb/Dockerfile)

dockerfile
FROM debian:bullseye

RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y mariadb-server && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*

COPY conf/my.cnf /etc/mysql/mariadb.conf.d/50-server.cnf

RUN mkdir -p /var/run/mysqld && chown -R mysql:mysql /var/run/mysqld

EXPOSE 3306

CMD ["mysqld_safe"]

6. WordPress container (srcs/requirements/wordpress/Dockerfile)

dockerfile
FROM debian:bullseye

RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y php-fpm php-mysql wget curl && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*

WORKDIR /var/www/html

RUN curl -O https://wordpress.org/latest.tar.gz \
    && tar -xvzf latest.tar.gz --strip-components=1 \
    && rm latest.tar.gz

COPY conf/www.conf /etc/php/7.4/fpm/pool.d/www.conf

EXPOSE 9000

CMD ["php-fpm7.4", "-F"]

7. NGINX container (srcs/requirements/nginx/Dockerfile)

dockerfile
FROM debian:bullseye

RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y nginx openssl && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*

RUN mkdir -p /etc/nginx/ssl
RUN openssl req -x509 -nodes -days 365 -newkey rsa:2048 \
    -keyout /etc/nginx/ssl/nginx.key \
    -out /etc/nginx/ssl/nginx.crt \
    -subj "/CN=yourlogin.42.fr"

COPY conf/nginx.conf /etc/nginx/nginx.conf

EXPOSE 443

CMD ["nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"]

8. Docker Compose (srcs/docker-compose.yml)

yaml
version: "3.8"

services:
  mariadb:
    build: ./requirements/mariadb
    container_name: mariadb
    restart: always
    env_file: .env
    volumes:
      - mariadb_data:/var/lib/mysql
    secrets:
      - db_root_password
      - db_password
    networks:
      - inception

  wordpress:
    build: ./requirements/wordpress
    container_name: wordpress
    restart: always
    env_file: .env
    volumes:
      - wordpress_data:/var/www/html
    depends_on:
      - mariadb
    networks:
      - inception

  nginx:
    build: ./requirements/nginx
    container_name: nginx
    restart: always
    ports:
      - "443:443"
    volumes:
      - wordpress_data:/var/www/html:ro
    depends_on:
      - wordpress
    networks:
      - inception

volumes:
  mariadb_data:
    driver: local
    driver_opts:
      type: none
      device: /home/yourlogin/data/mariadb
      o: bind
  wordpress_data:
    driver: local
    driver_opts:
      type: none
      device: /home/yourlogin/data/wordpress
      o: bind

networks:
  inception:

secrets:
  db_root_password:
    file: ../secrets/db_root_password.txt
  db_password:
    file: ../secrets/db_password.txt

9. Makefile

make
all: up

up:
	docker compose -f srcs/docker-compose.yml up --build -d

down:
	docker compose -f srcs/docker-compose.yml down

clean: down
	docker system prune -af --volumes

re: clean all

🔧 Config Files

1. NGINX (srcs/requirements/nginx/conf/nginx.conf)

This will:

  • Serve WordPress (via php-fpm at wordpress:9000).

  • Enforce TLS.

nginx
user  www-data;
worker_processes auto;

events {
    worker_connections 1024;
}

http {
    include       mime.types;
    default_type  application/octet-stream;
    sendfile      on;

    server {
        listen 443 ssl;
        server_name yourlogin.42.fr;

        ssl_certificate     /etc/nginx/ssl/nginx.crt;
        ssl_certificate_key /etc/nginx/ssl/nginx.key;

        root /var/www/html;
        index index.php index.html;

        location / {
            try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
        }

        location ~ \.php$ {
            include fastcgi_params;
            fastcgi_pass wordpress:9000;
            fastcgi_param SCRIPT_FILENAME $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;
            fastcgi_param PATH_INFO $fastcgi_path_info;
        }
    }
}

2. PHP-FPM (srcs/requirements/wordpress/conf/www.conf)

Configure PHP-FPM to listen on port 9000 (not a socket).

ini
[www]
user = www-data
group = www-data

listen = 0.0.0.0:9000

pm = dynamic
pm.max_children = 5
pm.start_servers = 2
pm.min_spare_servers = 1
pm.max_spare_servers = 3

catch_workers_output = yes

3. MariaDB (srcs/requirements/mariadb/conf/my.cnf)

Minimal secure config.

ini
[mysqld]
bind-address = 0.0.0.0
port = 3306
datadir = /var/lib/mysql
socket = /var/run/mysqld/mysqld.sock
symbolic-links=0

[client]
port = 3306
socket = /var/run/mysqld/mysqld.sock

4. MariaDB init script (srcs/requirements/mariadb/conf/init.sql)

You need at least one root user and one WordPress user.
(Docker will auto-run this if copied into /docker-entrypoint-initdb.d/)

sql
CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS wordpress;
CREATE USER IF NOT EXISTS 'wp_user'@'%' IDENTIFIED BY '$(cat /run/secrets/db_password)';
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON wordpress.* TO 'wp_user'@'%';
FLUSH PRIVILEGES;

👉 You’ll need to COPY this script in your MariaDB Dockerfile:

dockerfile
COPY conf/init.sql /docker-entrypoint-initdb.d/

🔐 Secrets Reminder

In /secrets/:

  • db_root_password.txt → SuperRootPass

  • db_password.txt → SuperWpPass

These are mounted inside containers at runtime (/run/secrets/...) and not in the image.

🚀 Build & Run

bash
make

  • NGINX → https://yourlogin.42.fr

  • WordPress → served behind NGINX

  • MariaDB → holds the DB

  • Volumes → /home/yourlogin/data/mariadb and /home/yourlogin/data/wordpress

⚠️ Gotchas (my opinion)

  • Most people fail this project because they try to hack it with tail -f or don’t understand PID 1. Don’t. Your CMD must always run the real process (nginx -g 'daemon off;', php-fpm -F, mysqld_safe).

  • Certificates: You’re fine with a self-signed cert for this project, but in real life, use Let’s Encrypt.

  • Keep secrets outside Git or you’ll fail instantly at evaluation.

🔹 Mandatory part

Project overview (questions)

  1. How Docker and docker-compose work
    “Docker builds images from Dockerfiles and runs containers. Each container runs one isolated service. Docker Compose is a higher-level tool that defines multiple services in one YAML file, sets up their networks and volumes, and orchestrates them together.”

  2. Difference between using images with/without Compose
    “Without Compose, you manage containers manually (docker run, docker network connect, etc.). With Compose, all services are defined in one file and run together with a single command (docker compose up).”

  3. Benefit of Docker vs VM
    “VMs emulate full operating systems with their own kernels, which is heavy. Docker uses the host kernel and isolates processes with namespaces and cgroups. That makes it lighter, faster to start, and more portable.”

  4. Why the directory structure matters
    “It enforces a clean separation: one folder per service with its Dockerfile and configs, a central srcs/ with compose, and a secrets/ folder outside Git. This ensures readability, maintainability, and security.”

Here’s how I’d approach it:

🧠 How to Really Understand Inception

1. One service = one container

  • MariaDB: database only, persistent data in /home/<login>/data/mariadb.

  • WordPress (php-fpm): runs PHP code, no NGINX inside.

  • NGINX: the gatekeeper, handles HTTPS and forwards PHP requests to WordPress.

👉 Why? Because containers are meant to be single-process units. Splitting services keeps them clean and replaceable.

2. Separation of concerns

  • NGINX: reverse proxy, SSL/TLS termination.

  • WordPress: application logic.

  • MariaDB: data storage.
    If one crashes, others can still run. This is the Docker philosophy.

3. Networking

  • Containers can’t talk directly unless you create a docker network.

  • In your case, Compose creates a bridge network (inception).

  • Inside that network, containers can talk by service name:

    • nginx → wordpress:9000

    • wordpress → mariadb:3306

👉 You must be able to explain this clearly in defense.

4. Persistence

  • By default, containers are ephemeral. If you restart them, data is lost.

  • That’s why you bind volumes:

    • /home/<login>/data/wordpress → site files

    • /home/<login>/data/mariadb → database

  • This is why after reboot, WordPress is still configured.

👉 Evaluators love this explanation because it shows you know why volumes matter.

5. Security best practices

  • No passwords in Dockerfiles (use .env + secrets).

  • No tail -f hacks — real daemons must be run properly.

  • Only expose port 443 (not 80, not DB).

  • Admin username must not contain admin.

👉 If you can explain why these rules exist (security + clean container philosophy), you’ll shine.

6. Why Docker instead of VMs

  • VM = full OS → heavier, slower.

  • Docker = lightweight process isolation → faster, portable, consistent.

  • Example: starting a VM might take 30s+, while a container starts in under a second.

7. Common pitfalls you must avoid

  • Accidentally exposing MariaDB port outside.

  • Forgetting TLS.

  • Leaving WordPress installation page (means DB isn’t linked correctly).

  • Using latest tag in Dockerfiles.

  • Not persisting volumes.

🎯 How to Prepare for Defense

  • Practice explaining:

    • “What happens when I go to https://login.42.fr?”
      → Browser hits NGINX (TLS), NGINX proxies PHP requests to WordPress, WordPress queries MariaDB, response goes back through NGINX → browser.

  • Do a live DB check: log in to MariaDB, show tables.

  • Do a WordPress check: log in as admin, edit a page.

  • Show persistence: reboot VM, prove WordPress config is still there.

The Inception project is not about making a website — it’s about understanding infrastructure.
If you can confidently explain:

  • why containers are separated,

  • how they communicate,

  • how persistence works,

  • why TLS is mandatory,
    you will pass with no problem.

Why: That’s where WordPress files live.

dockerfile

→ Download, extract, and clean WordPress.
Why: Always ship fresh WordPress.

→ Replace PHP-FPM config with your version.
Why: Needed to listen on TCP port 9000 instead of socket.

→ Show that service is on port 9000.
Why: NGINX will forward PHP requests here.

dockerfile
CMD ["php-fpm7.4", "-F"]

→ Run PHP-FPM in foreground.
Why: Foreground mode is required inside Docker (PID 1 must stay alive).

🔹 NGINX Dockerfile

dockerfile
FROM debian:bullseye

→ Base Debian system.

dockerfile
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y nginx openssl && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*

→ Install NGINX and OpenSSL (for self-signed cert).
Why: TLS required.

dockerfile
RUN mkdir -p /etc/nginx/ssl

→ Create SSL directory.

dockerfile
RUN openssl req -x509 -nodes -days 365 -newkey rsa:2048 \
    -keyout /etc/nginx/ssl/nginx.key \
    -out /etc/nginx/ssl/nginx.crt \
    -subj "/CN=yourlogin.42.fr"

→ Generate a self-signed SSL certificate.
Why: Mandatory TLS, cert doesn’t need to be trusted by browser.

dockerfile
COPY conf/nginx.conf /etc/nginx/nginx.conf

→ Copy your custom config.
Why: To enforce TLS, set reverse proxy rules.

dockerfile
EXPOSE 443

→ Container listens on HTTPS port.

dockerfile
CMD ["nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"]

→ Run NGINX in foreground.
Why: Daemon mode would background the process, container would stop.

yaml

→ Compose file version.

      - inception

→ WordPress service: built from Dockerfile, shares volume for site files, depends on mariadb (starts after DB), in same network.

    depends_on:
      - wordpress
    networks:
      - inception

→ NGINX service: listens on host 443, shares WordPress volume read-only, starts after WordPress, only entrypoint.

yaml

  mariadb_data:

      type: none

Why: ensures persistence after reboot.

  inception:

→ Custom network, isolates services from outside.

Why: safer than putting passwords in repo.

⚙️ Config Files

🔹 nginx.conf

nginx
server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    server_name yourlogin.42.fr;

    ssl_certificate     /etc/nginx/ssl/nginx.crt;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/nginx/ssl/nginx.key;

    root /var/www/html;
    index index.php index.html;

    location / {
        try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
    }

    location ~ \.php$ {
        include fastcgi_params;
        fastcgi_pass wordpress:9000;
        fastcgi_param SCRIPT_FILENAME $document_root$fastcgi_script_name;
        fastcgi_param PATH_INFO $fastcgi_path_info;
    }
}

  • listen 443 ssl: only HTTPS.

  • ssl_certificate: use your self-signed cert.

  • root: points to WordPress files.

  • try_files: serve static files if exist, else 404.

  • location ~ .php$: forward PHP requests to WordPress container on port 9000.

🔹 www.conf (PHP-FPM)

ini
listen = 0.0.0.0:9000

→ PHP-FPM listens on port 9000, not socket.
Why: So NGINX in another container can reach it.

🔹 my.cnf (MariaDB)

ini
bind-address = 0.0.0.0

→ Allow connections from other containers, not just localhost.
Why: Needed for WordPress to connect.

🚀 Summary

  • Dockerfiles: build minimal images with just enough tools to run one service.

  • docker-compose.yml: glues services together, handles volumes, networks, secrets.

  • Configs: fine-tune behavior (nginx proxying, PHP port, DB binding).

During defense, don’t just say “this line installs MariaDB”. Add why:

  • “I clean apt cache because otherwise the image would be unnecessarily large.”

  • “I run NGINX in foreground because Docker containers die if PID 1 exits.”

  • “I use a volume because containers are ephemeral.”

That “why” is what makes you sound like you understand, not just copy-pasted.

  3. You keep credentials.txt for yourself so you don’t forget what you set.

Keep the passwords different (root vs WordPress user). Evaluators often check that you understand root ≠ app user.

Vous avez dit :
i have run in some error and needs to rebuild the whole thing. how can i remove cached infos and rebuild like its the first time ?
ChatGPT a dit :

Good call 👍 — Docker caches layers, images, volumes, and networks, so if you want a clean rebuild (like first time), you need to wipe them.

Here’s a step-by-step reset checklist:

🧹 Full Docker Reset (like fresh install)

⚠️ Warning: this will delete all containers, images, volumes, and networks. Be careful if you have other Docker projects.

1. Stop and remove all containers

bash
docker stop $(docker ps -qa)
docker rm -f $(docker ps -qa)

2. Remove all images

bash
docker rmi -f $(docker images -qa)

3. Remove all volumes (⚠️ wipes persistent data)

bash
docker volume rm $(docker volume ls -q)

4. Remove all networks (except default)

bash
docker network rm $(docker network ls -q) 2>/dev/null

🔄 Rebuild your project

Now go back to your project root and run:

bash
make re

This will:

  • Rebuild Docker images from scratch (no cache).

  • Recreate volumes fresh.

  • Recreate networks fresh.

🧪 If you want a “semi-clean” rebuild

Sometimes you just want to rebuild without cache but keep volumes:

bash
docker compose -f srcs/docker-compose.yml build --no-cache
docker compose -f srcs/docker-compose.yml up -d

📌 Quick Cleanup Shortcut

If you want a one-liner for your Makefile clean target:

make
clean:
	docker stop $$(docker ps -qa) || true
	docker rm -f $$(docker ps -qa) || true
	docker rmi -f $$(docker images -qa) || true
	docker volume rm $$(docker volume ls -q) || true
	docker network rm $$(docker network ls -q) 2>/dev/null || true

👉 My opinion:
When debugging, it’s better to rebuild without cache (--no-cache) first. Only do a full nuke (remove volumes + networks) if things are really broken, because otherwise you’ll waste time re-installing WordPress after every test.

Vous avez dit :
i always get this error tho : ✔ Volume "srcs_mariadb_data" Created 0.0s ✘ Container mariadb Error response from daemon: failed to populate volume: error while mounting volume '/var/lib/docker/volumes/srcs_mariadb_data/_data': fai... 0.0s Error response from daemon: failed to populate volume: error while mounting volume '/var/lib/docker/volumes/srcs_mariadb_data/_data': failed to mount local volume: mount /home/pcmr/data/mariadb:/var/lib/docker/volumes/srcs_mariadb_data/_data, flags: 0x1000: no such file or directory make: *** [Makefile:4: up] Error 1
ChatGPT a dit :

Ah, I see exactly what’s happening here 👀

The error:

swift
failed to mount local volume: mount /home/pcmr/data/mariadb:/var/lib/docker/volumes/srcs_mariadb_data/_data, flags: 0x1000: no such file or directory

means that Docker is trying to mount a host directory that doesn’t exist yet.

🔎 Why this happens

In your docker-compose.yml, you have something like:

yaml
volumes:
  mariadb_data:
    driver: local
    driver_opts:
      type: none
      device: /home/pcmr/data/mariadb
      o: bind

But on your machine, /home/pcmr/data/mariadb does not exist.
Docker cannot bind-mount into a non-existing folder → container fails.

✅ Fix

1. Create the directories manually

Run:

bash
mkdir -p /home/pcmr/data/mariadb
mkdir -p /home/pcmr/data/wordpress

Now Docker will be able to mount them.

2. Check permissions

Make sure Docker can write there:

bash
ls -ld /home/pcmr/data/*

If permissions are too strict, fix with:

bash
chmod -R 755 /home/pcmr/data

3. Rebuild clean

Once folders exist, rebuild without cache:

bash
docker compose -f srcs/docker-compose.yml down -v
docker compose -f srcs/docker-compose.yml build --no-cache
docker compose -f srcs/docker-compose.yml up -d

💡 My recommendation

To avoid this forever, add a Makefile target to auto-create the data folders before running docker compose up.

make
setup:
	mkdir -p /home/pcmr/data/mariadb
	mkdir -p /home/pcmr/data/wordpress

up: setup
	docker compose -f srcs/docker-compose.yml up -d --build

👉 My opinion:
This is the #1 error in Inception defenses. Evaluators will sometimes delete your /home/<login>/data before testing persistence. If your Makefile recreates it automatically, you’ll impress them.

✅ MANDATORY PART — PERFECT ANSWERS

🧩 1. PROJECT OVERVIEW

Q: “Explain how Docker works.”

“Docker creates isolated environments called containers. Each container runs one service with its own filesystem, processes, and configuration, but all share the host kernel. Images are templates used to build containers.”

Q: “Explain how docker-compose works.”

“Docker Compose describes multiple services in a single YAML file. It builds images, sets up networks, volumes, and starts all containers with one command.”

Q: “Difference between using Docker alone vs docker-compose?”

“With Docker alone, you would manually run each container and set up networks/volumes. With Compose, everything is orchestrated automatically with a single command.”

Q: “Why is Docker better than VMs?”

“VMs run full operating systems (heavy, slow to boot). Containers reuse the host kernel (light, fast, portable).”

Q: “Why this directory structure?”

“It separates concerns: each service has its own config + Dockerfile, srcs/ groups the whole system, and Makefile automates everything. It matches best practices and the subject’s expectations.”
